Catholic resistance during the Enlightenment revolutions
Part of: Religion and politics in the Age of Revolutions
Overview
Periodc. 1780–1815
RegionsFrance; Habsburg lands; Italian peninsula; Papal States; Spain
Immediate causesCivil Constitution of the Clergy (1790); Josephinist reforms; suppression of religious orders; confiscation of church property
Key modesRefusal of oaths; clandestine worship; pastoral letters and papal briefs; royalist insurgencies; émigré networks; polemical literature
OutcomesConcordat of 1801; partial restoration of worship; consolidation of state control in many areas; 19th‑century Catholic revival and ultramontanism
Notable figuresPius VI; Pius VII; Ercole Consalvi; Fabrizio Ruffo; Joseph de Maistre; Louis de Bonald; Augustin Barruel; François‑René de Chateaubriand; Henry Essex Edgeworth
